04574nam a22006015i 9780226537344DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20182018ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017030693  a9780226537344  a(DE-B1597)521377  a(OCoLC)1028979506  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aBR115.H6bL48 2018 7aSOC0000002bisacsh  aBE 5650qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/10596:1 aLewin, Ellen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFilled with the Spirit :bSexuality, Gender, and Radical Inclusivity in a Black Pentecostal Church Coalition /cEllen Lewin. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b3 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tInvocation: The Anthropology Ministry -- t1 “I’ve Been ’Buked”: The Double Consciousness of Being LGBT and Black -- t2. “Lead Me, Guide Me”: The Charisma of Bishop Flunder -- t3. “Just as I Am”: Revealing Authentic Selves -- t4. “Old-Time Religion”: Invoking Memory -- t5. “What a Fellowship”: Radically Inclusive Futures -- tBenediction: Continuities and Departures -- tNotes -- tReferences Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 2001, a collection of open and affirming churches with predominantly African American membership and a Pentecostal style of worship formed a radically new coalition. The group, known now as the Fellowship of Affirming Ministries or TFAM, has at its core the idea of “radical inclusivity”: the powerful assertion that everyone, no matter how seemingly flawed or corrupted, has holiness within. Whether you are LGBT, have HIV/AIDS, have been in prison, abuse drugs or alcohol, are homeless, or are otherwise compromised and marginalized, TFAM tells its people, you are one of God’s creations. In Filled with the Spirit, Ellen Lewin gives us a deeply empathetic ethnography of the worship and community central to TFAM, telling the story of how the doctrine of radical inclusivity has expanded beyond those it originally sought to serve to encompass people of all races, genders, sexualities, and religious backgrounds. Lewin examines the seemingly paradoxical relationship between TFAM and traditional black churches, focusing on how congregations and individual members reclaim the worship practices of these churches and simultaneously challenge their authority. The book looks closely at how TFAM worship is legitimated and enhanced by its use of gospel music and considers the images of food and African American culture that are central to liturgical imagery, as well as how understandings of personal authenticity tie into the desire to be filled with the Holy Spirit. Throughout, Lewin takes up what has been mostly missing from our discussions of race, gender, and sexuality—close attention to spirituality and faith.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAfrican American sexual minoritiesxReligious life. 0aHomosexualityxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aPentecostalism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aAfrican American culture.  aLGBT religion.  aPentecostalism.  acharisma.  aradical inclusivity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106885800 cprintz978022653717740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226537344423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226537344/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-073776-9  DTL Humanities 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles